The single most important fact about both movies and television is that the=
y were defined by scarcity: there were only so many movies that would ever =
be made to fill only so many theater slots, and in the case of TV, there we=
re only 24 hours in a day. That meant that there was significant value in b=
eing someone who could figure out what was going to be a hit before it was =
ever created, and then investing to make it so. That sort of selection and =
production is what Katzenberg and the rest of Hollywood have been doing for=
 decades, and it=E2=80=99s understandable that Katzenberg thought he could =
apply the same formula to mobile. Mobile, though, is defined by the Interne=
t, which is to say it is defined by abundance=E2=80=A6

So it is on TikTok, or any other app with user-generated content. The goal =
is not to pick out the hits, but rather to attract as much content as possi=
ble, and then algorithmically boost whatever turns out to be good.

This is the consumer-facing manifestation of a model that embraces churn on=
 the supplier side: by dramatically increasing the amount of content availa=
ble, you get in terms of both absolute volume and on a percentage basis far=
 more dreck; critically, though, the amount of content is so great that the=
 absolute volume of good stuff is higher too.

Indeed, this is why Netflix=E2=80=99s biggest threat is arguably YouTube: N=
etflix=E2=80=99s hit rate in terms of content produced is, on a percentage =
basis, dramatically higher, but YouTube has such an advantage in absolutely=
 amount of content =E2=80=94 acquired for free =E2=80=94 that on an absolut=
e basis it has more quality content than anyone. Granted, this doesn=E2=80=
=99t fully extend into fully scripted content, but the gap is and will cont=
inue to close.

