This is the payoff from nurturing and creating an ecosystem that is only po=
ssible on your platform: the content you foster on your platform and your p=
latform become self-reinforcing.

Ostroff, Simmons, and Harry
---------------------------

A memo from Spotify CEO Daniel Ek ( https://newsroom.spotify.com/2023-01-23=
/an-update-on-january-2023-organizational-changes/ ) from earlier this year=
 announced layoffs, and included this bit of executive news:

As a part of this change, Dawn Ostroff has decided to depart Spotify. Dawn =
has made a tremendous mark not only on Spotify, but on the audio industry o=
verall. Because of her efforts, Spotify grew our podcast content by 40x, dr=
ove significant innovation in the medium and became the leading music and p=
odcast service in many markets. These investments in audio offered new oppo=
rtunities for music and podcast creators and also drove new interest in the=
 potential of Spotify=E2=80=99s audio advertising. Thanks to her work, Spot=
ify was able to innovate on the ads format itself and more than double the =
revenue of our advertising business to =E2=82=AC1.5 billion. We are enormou=
sly grateful for the pivotal role she has played and wish her much success.=
 In the near term, Dawn will assume the role of senior advisor to help faci=
litate this transition. Alex will take on the responsibility for the conten=
t, advertising and licensing work going forward and you=E2=80=99ll hear mor=
e from him on that.

Ostroff came from Hollywood, and it seems fair to assume that, like Jeffrey=
 Katzenberg, she came with the Hollywood mindset that celebrity is scarce, =
and thus critical for overcoming scarcity; like Quibi, though, Spotify is c=
ompeting in a world defined by abundance. This, by extension, gives special=
 resonance to Simmons=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cembarass[ment]=E2=80=9D about shari=
ng a platform with Harry: sure, he was famous, but that=E2=80=99s because t=
here are only so many royal family members; Simmons is famous because he wo=
rked himself up from obscurity through his writing and podcasting.

In other words, I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s an accident that Simmons=
 is still at Spotify, and Ostroff is not =E2=80=94 and that The Ringer is t=
he one Spotify content acquisition that appears to still be growing, instea=
d of facing layoffs.

To put it another way, while I talked about abundance in the context of the=
 platform and in the context of users above, Simmons=E2=80=99 complaint abo=
ut Harry is best understood in the context of the creator: at the end of th=
e day you only win on the Internet by being consistently excellent. Simmons=
 has been podcasting and/or writing for nearly three decades, and to the ex=
tent he has a leg up because of his audience that is a function of his writ=
ing being compelling in the first place. Harry, meanwhile, was =E2=80=9Cbor=
n in a royal family and then [he] left=E2=80=9D; that gets you no where on =
the Internet, but it does get you paid by executives who apply the wrong fr=
ame of competition to a world of zero marginal cost content.

